      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm working on this embedded c++ project and the heap just keeps growing until it crashes. i think there's a leak somewhere in this loop but i cant find it. can u take a look?\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n\nvoid process_sensor_data() {\n    int* data_buffer = new int[100];\n    \n    // Simulate sensor reading\n    for(int i = 0; i < 100; ++i) {\n        data_buffer[i] = i * 2;\n    }\n\n    if (data_buffer[50] > 50) {\n        std::cout << \"Data threshold reached\" << std::endl;\n        // logic goes here\n    }\n    \n    // i thought i was deleting it but it's still leaking\n}\n\nint main() {\n    while(true) {\n        process_sensor_data();\n    }\n    return 0;\n}\n```",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The heap leak is indeed a common issue in C++. You're right on the right track by suspecting a leak in the loop. However, the issue here is not just about finding the leak, but also about understanding why the memory isn't being freed.\n\nIn this case, the problem lies in the fact that you're not deleting the dynamically allocated memory after you're done using it. The `data_buffer` is local to the `process_sensor_data` function, which means it will be automatically destroyed when the function returns. But, the memory it points to is not being freed, so the heap continues to grow.\n\nYou can fix this by adding a `delete[]` statement after the loop, like so:\n\n```cpp\nvoid process_sensor_data() {\n    int* data_buffer = new int[100];\n    \n    // Simulate sensor reading\n    for(int i = 0; i < 100; ++i) {\n        data_buffer[i] = i * 2;\n    }\n\n    if (data_buffer[50] > 50) {\n        std::cout << \"Data threshold reached\" << std::endl;\n        // logic goes here\n    }\n    \n    // Free the memory\n    delete[] data_buffer",
